  {
    "bookmark_id": "1761771742240924066",
    "status_id": "1761771742240924066",
    "status_url": "https://x.com/yilmazkuday/status/1761771742240924066",
    "author_name": "HAKAN YILMAZKUDAY",
    "handle": "yilmazkuday",
    "text": "Using monthly headline inflation data covering 184 countries, this paper investigates the role of standard gravity variables on inflation convergence across countries. https://t.co/q2VFNQq32h\n\nThe convergence analysis by unit root tests is based on ten-year rolling windows to control for potential structural changes over time, whereas the corresponding results are connected to the standard gravity variables in the preceding year to investigate the drivers of inflation convergence and its speed. \n\nRegarding the existence of inflation convergence, empirical results show that having a common currency, a free trade agreement, proximity, a common border, or a colonial relationship between countries increases the probability of inflation convergence. \n\nRegarding the speed of inflation convergence, the very same gravity variables are shown to reduce the half-life of convergence. \n\nIn both cases, the effects of having a common currency are shown to dominate those of other gravity variables.",
    "language": "en",
    "hashtags": [],
    "urls": [
      "https://doi.org/10.1017/S1365100522000396"
    ],
    "media": [
      "https://pbs.twimg.com/media/GHMR4TkXcAAS9e-.jpg"
    ],
    "quoted_status_urls": [],
